700":"1618–1700","1653–1715":"1653–1715","1600–1679":"1600–1679","1679":"1679","1700":"1700","1600":"1600","1642":"1642","1653":"1653","1651":"1651","about 1653":"about 1653","1607":"1607","1618":"1618","2 June 1679":"2 June 1679","1715":"1715","1637":"1637","Henrico, Virginia, British Colonial America":"Henrico, Virginia, British Colonial America","Great Oakley, Northamptonshire, England":"Great Oakley, Northamptonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rowlett","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from a diminutive of the personal name <i>Rol(l)and</i>. See   Rowland   and compare   Rolling  .","English: from a pet form of the personal name   Ralph  . Compare   Rawling  .","English: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Rolf</i>. See   Rolfe   and compare   Rolling  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Rowlette","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Collette, Lucien.","Variant of   Rowlett  , a surname of English or French origin."]},{"name":"Roulette","meanings":["Altered form of English   Rowlett  .","French: unexplained. In North America, this surname may also be an altered form of   Roulet  , reflecting the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>."]},{"name":"Rowland","meanings":["English: from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Rollant</i>, <i>Rolant</i>, <i>Rolent</i>, <i>Roulent</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Hrodland</i>, <i>Rodland</i>, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘glory’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’), introduced into England by the Normans. It was made famous by French romances about <i>Roland</i>, the most famous of the peers of Charlemagne who was killed at Roncesvalles in  AD  778. Although widely used across post-Conquest England (along with <i>Oliver</i>, the name of Roland's companion), it seems to have been restricted to particular gentry families and was never popular. Compare   Roland  .","English: habitational name from Rowland (Derbyshire) or Rowland Wood in Slinfold (Sussex). The Derbyshire placename derives from Old Norse <i>rá</i> ‘roe, roe buck’ or <i>rá</i> ‘land mark, boundary’ + <i>lúndr</i> ‘small wood, grove’. The Sussex placename probably derives from Middle English <i>roughe</i> ‘rough’ + <i>lond</i> ‘land’ (Old English <i>rūh</i>, <i>land</i>).","English: in northern England and perhaps elsewhere, perhaps a post-medieval variant of   Rawling  . Compare   Rawlinson  ,   Rollinson  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705210,"age":0,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1357536,"age":7,"year":"1607","julianDay":2308005,"description":"The Virginia Company founded the first permanent English colony at Jamestown in 1607. One of the original 13 states (it entered the Union in 1788). Virginia holds an important place in American history, as it was home to many of the founding fathers, including George Washington, Thomas Jefferson, James Madison, George Mason, and Patrick Henry. Four of Americas first five presidents were Virginians. During the Civil War, Richmond, Virginias capital, was the capital of the Confederacy. Today, Virginia is a popular tourist spot where people can visit historic places such as Alexandria, Williamsburg, and Mount Vernon, George Washingtons estate.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705213,"age":42,"year":"1642","toYear":"1651","julianDay":2320789,"title":"The English Civil War","description":"A series of conflicts regarding England's governance during the years 1642 to 1651 is now known as The English Civil War. Charles I summoned supporters to join him against his enemies in Parliament. In October 1642, nearly 10,000 men fought for Charles I and chased Parliament across the River Tamar. Fighting continued for years and was finally ended at the Battle of Worcester on September 3, 1651, with a Parliamentarian victory.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"John Rowlett was born in 1600, in Great Oakley, Northamptonshire, England. He married Mary Bray in 1637. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died on 2 June 1679, in Henrico, Virginia, British Colonial America, at the age of 79."},"et":{"1600–2 June 1679":"1600–2. juuni 1679","1618–1700":"1618–1700","1653–1715":"1653–1715","1600–1679":"1600–1679","1679":"1679","1700":"1700","1600":"1600","1642":"1642","1653":"1653","1651":"1651","about 1653":"umbes 1653","1607":"1607","1618":"1618","2 June 1679":"2. juuni 1679","1715":"1715","1637":"1637","Henrico, Virginia, British Colonial America":"Henrico, Virginia, British Colonial America","Great Oakley, Northamptonshire, England":"Great Oakley, Northamptonshire, England"},"fi":{"1600–2 June 1679":"1600–2. kesäkuuta 1679","1618–1700":"1618–1700","1653–1715":"1653–1715","1600–1679":"1600–1679","1679":"1679","1700":"1700","1600":"1600","1642":"1642","1653":"1653","1651":"1651","about 1653":"noin 1653","1607":"1607","1618":"1618","2 June 1679":"2. kesäkuuta 1679","1715":"1715","1637":"1637","Henrico, Virginia, British Colonial America":"Henrico, Virginia, British Colonial America","Great Oakley, Northamptonshire, England":"Great Oakley, Northamptonshire, England"},"fr":{"1600–2 June 1679":"1600–2 juin 1679","1618–1700":"1618–1700","16